      <scopecontent id="aspace_8857dd208fbb5d9b1ade087980c5cc3a">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The School of Forestry and Environmental Studies Library records consist of accession lists, annual reports, classification files, library guides, photographs and a plaque honoring Dr. Frances Mary Bolton.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_65d32032f0abef59607de974594244ee">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The School of Forestry Library was established in Marsh Hall with the founding of the school in 1900.  The core of the collection was donated by the first dean of the school, Henry S. Graves.  Graves is also credited with developing the library's first classification scheme, known as Yale Forestry Classification.  The library was renamed the Henry S. Graves Memorial Library in honor of Graves in 1953. The school itself was later renamed the School of Forestry and Environmental Studies and the library was often referred to as the School of Forestry and Environmental Studies Library.  The library moved in 1923 to Sage Hall and again in 2009 to Kroon Hall where it remained until it closed in 2010 to become part of the Center for Science and Social Science Information.</p>  
      </bioghist>
